node.text:
The U.S. military carried out a drone strike in Afghanistan on August 29 that killed 10 people including 7 children, citing intelligence about a car with explosive material inside. CNN investigated the U.S. military claims about the strike, conducting interviews ‘that paint a very different version of events.’

U.S. Gen. Kenneth McKenzie Jr. has since apologized for the civilian deaths, stating ‘we now assess that it is unlikely the vehicle and those who died were associated with ISIS-K’

#dronevideo #military #dronestrike #afghanistan #investigation

node.title: Investigating a U.S. Drone Strike in Afghanistan

A Food and Drug Administration advisory panel decided on Friday to recommend against a plan to begin providing booster shots of the Pfizer/BioNTech vaccine for members of the general public who have already received 2 doses of the vaccine. ⁠
⁠
Though officials on the White House’s own coronavirus response team have been laying out plans to begin distributing booster shots at some point in September, the panel voted 16-2 against approving boosters for those 16 and older. The panel did, however, recommend administering boosters to benefit certain populations, like older adults and those with high risk factors who could suffer acutely if infected by COVID-19.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Washington, D.C.'s National Mall has been transformed into a sea of white to honor the lives lost to COVID-19 in the U.S.—more than 670,000 of them.⁠
⁠
An early form of the memorial was first displayed by artist Suzanne Brennan Firstenberg in October 2020 outside of RFK Stadium. Since then, the number of flags symbolizing someone lost to COVID-19 has dramatically—and sadly—increased. Firstenberg says she was inspired to create the installations after a Texas official said the economy was worth Americans risking dying of COVID-19. 'I just felt as though someone had to do something to make a statement that with all these people dying, we had to value each of these lives as well,' according to NPR.⁠
⁠
Family members and friends of COVID-19 victims have left small messages on the flags. Some of the flags have even been selected to be displayed at the Smithsonian National Museum of American History.⁠
⁠
The flag installation will be on display from September 17 to October 3, 2021, per Firstenberg's website.⁠
⁠
⁠
#covid19 #covid #washingtondc #pandemic
